docs.abstract: President Trump all but endorsed his former campaign manager, who is weighing a Senate bid. “He’s terrific on television,” Mr. Trump said. “I like everything about him.”
docs.snippet: President Trump all but endorsed his former campaign manager, who is weighing a Senate bid. “He’s terrific on television,” Mr. Trump said. “I like everything about him.”
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump on Thursday all but endorsed his former campaign manager, Corey Lewandowski, for a potential Senate run from New Hampshire, saying he would be “hard to beat” if he ran and a “great senator” if he won.

headline.main: Trump Thinks Corey Lewandowski Would Be a ‘Fantastic’ Senator From New Hampshire
headline.print_headline: Ex-Campaign Chief ‘Great’ For Senate, President Says

docs.abstract: Democratic candidates are pushing ideas that were considered radical just a few years ago. But the American public has changed its views, too.
docs.snippet: Democratic candidates are pushing ideas that were considered radical just a few years ago. But the American public has changed its views, too.
docs.lead_paragraph: Marijuana would be decriminalized, mass incarceration would be reversed and the death penalty would be eliminated as part of sweeping changes that leading Democratic presidential candidates have proposed to make to the criminal justice system, which has become a dependable political foil for its inefficiency and excesses but has also proved resistant to change.

headline.main: The Criminal Justice Debate Has Changed Drastically. Here’s Why.
headline.print_headline: With Calls for Reform, 2020 Candidates Shift Criminal Justice Debate

docs.lead_paragraph: A rabbi in St. Louis Park, Minn., was more than six thousand miles from Jerusalem when he heard the Israeli government decided to bar two Muslim members of Congress from making an official visit to the Jewish state.

docs.abstract: Ms. Klobuchar, a senator from Minnesota, has focused on issues that can attract bipartisan support.
docs.snippet: Ms. Klobuchar, a senator from Minnesota, has focused on issues that can attract bipartisan support.
docs.lead_paragraph: Pragmatism is at the center of Senator Amy Klobuchar’s run for the Democratic presidential nomination. Ask what makes her uniquely qualified to be president, and she’s likely to remind you that she’s from the Midwest and has a long record of getting things done in Congress.

headline.main: Amy Klobuchar on Her Record and Bipartisanship

docs.abstract: Ms. Warren wants to tax the 75,000 wealthiest families in the United States and reduce inequality.
docs.snippet: Ms. Warren wants to tax the 75,000 wealthiest families in the United States and reduce inequality.
docs.lead_paragraph: By now, Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts is known for being the candidate ready with a plan. But back in January, she was just getting her campaign started. And one of her very first proposals was to impose a wealth tax.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren on a Wealth Tax

docs.abstract: Ms. Warren has proposed a $1.25 trillion plan that would wipe out most student debt.
docs.snippet: Ms. Warren has proposed a $1.25 trillion plan that would wipe out most student debt.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts has structured her presidential campaign around a series of disruptive policy ideas. One of her biggest involves reshaping higher education by canceling most student loan debt and eliminating tuition at public colleges.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren on Free College and Canceling Student Debt
